questions.statement:
&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Which of the following sentences is/are grammatically correct among the three given below?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;A.&amp;nbsp;Sooner had Amrita come from work than her friends organized a get-together.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;B.&amp;nbsp;Each day, the journey from college to his home takes him an hour.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;C.&amp;nbsp;After disposing of the stolen items, the thief was found.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Only B and C&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Statement A:&lt;/span&gt;​

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This sentence is structurally wrong.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;If the second event occurs immediately after the first, we can express that idea using the structure &amp;quot;no sooner &amp;hellip; than.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is often used with the past perfect and usually followed by &amp;#39;than&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;ldquo;No sooner&amp;hellip; than&amp;rdquo; is correlative conjunction. These types of conjunctions work in pairs and relate one sentence to another.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Therefore, statement A is grammatically incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The correct sentence should be: &lt;em&gt;No sooner&amp;nbsp;had Amrita come from work than her friends organized a get-together.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;​&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Statement B:&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;We use &amp;quot;verb+s&amp;quot; to refer to a third-person singular subject.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;His&amp;quot; refers to the third-person singular subject and for that reason the singular verb &amp;quot;takes&amp;quot; is used.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;We know that subjects and verbs must agree with one another in number (singular or plural).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The preposition &amp;#39;from&amp;#39; is used to describe the&amp;nbsp;transport route.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Therefore, statement B is grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Statement C:&lt;/span&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The preposition &amp;#39;of&amp;#39; is always used after &amp;#39;dispose&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;Dispose of&amp;quot; means&amp;nbsp;to get rid of something or deal with something so that the matter is finished.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The sentence tells that the burglar was caught after getting rid of the stolen goods.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Therefore, statement C is grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Option 1,&amp;nbsp;Only B and C&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;the developed countries economies&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Economy&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is a singular noun that refers to the economic system of a country.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Economies&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is the plural form of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;economy&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;In the given sentence, the phrase &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;the developed countries economies&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is grammatically incorrect because &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;economies&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; should be replaced with &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;economy&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; to maintain singular-plural agreement.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;​&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;The developing countries began to copy and re-create aspects of &lt;strong&gt;the developed country&amp;#39;s economy&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1)&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;The developing countries began&amp;quot; is grammatically correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2)&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;to copy and re-create aspects of&amp;quot; is grammatically correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4)&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;No Error&amp;quot; is incorrect because there is an error in the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;B.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the above-given sentence, the error is in part B.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;I&lt;/strong&gt;t is so because&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;There are some plural forms of the noun which are actually singular. They take singular verb with them&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For Example - Innings, mathematics, &lt;strong&gt;news&lt;/strong&gt;, civics, politics, ethics, physics, economics, mechanics, summons, measles, mumps, rickets, singles, billiards, athletics etc.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example sentence&lt;/strong&gt; - Mathematics&lt;strong&gt; is &lt;/strong&gt;an easy subject.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;were&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; will be replaced by &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;was&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the correct sentence is&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;This news &lt;strong&gt;was &lt;/strong&gt;of little consolation to us.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If plural-looking subjects are &lt;strong&gt;particularized&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;possessed&lt;/strong&gt;, they become &lt;strong&gt;plural nouns&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For Example:-&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;My mathematics &lt;strong&gt;are &lt;/strong&gt;strong.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The politics of our country &lt;strong&gt;are&lt;/strong&gt; dirty.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/hinglish-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hinglish&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;ऊपर दिए गए वाक्य में, त्रुटि &lt;strong&gt;भाग B&lt;/strong&gt; में है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;इसलिए है क्योंकि&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;संज्ञा के कुछ बहुवचन रूप हैं जो वास्तव में एकवचन हैं। वे अपने साथ singular verb लेते हैं &amp;rsquo;।&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;उदाहरण के लिए -&amp;nbsp;Innings, mathematics,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;news&lt;/span&gt;, civics, politics, ethics, physics, economics, mechanics, summons, measles, mumps, rickets, singles, billiards, athletics etc.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;उदाहरण वाक्य&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;-&amp;nbsp;Mathematics&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;an easy subject.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;इस प्रकार,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;were&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;को&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;was&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;से बदल दिया जाएगा&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;।&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;इसलिए, सही वाक्य&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;This news was of little consolation to us.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;It was him&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In English grammar, the pronoun after &amp;quot;to be&amp;quot; verb (is, am, are, was, were etc.) should be in nominative case, not in objective case.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So &amp;quot;He&amp;quot; should be used instead of &amp;quot;him.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Phrase &amp;quot;who came running&amp;quot; is correctly constructed, where &amp;quot;who&amp;quot; is a relative pronoun referring to &amp;quot;It&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;Came running&amp;quot; is a verb phrase implying the action done by the person.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;Into the classroom&amp;quot; is also correct, indicating the direction of the action.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is Option 1 &amp;#39;It was him&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A Pronoun must agree with its antecedent in person, number, and gender.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, the pronoun and verb come according to the antecedent&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Each.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Also, we talk about&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;boys&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;so the masculine form(&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;his&lt;/span&gt;) is used.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence,&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;option 2&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is the correct answer.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Thus the correct sentence is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Each of these boys does &lt;strong&gt;his &lt;/strong&gt;work because of exam pressure.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When the pronouns &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Each, every, neither, either, anyone, many a, more than one(possessive adjective)&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;are used as the subject, the possessive case should be third person singular. They may refer to two or more than two objects or persons.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Each one of us is doing&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;our&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;duty properly.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; (Use &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;his&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39; in place of&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;our&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39;)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Everyone should do&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;one&amp;#39;s&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;duty.&amp;nbsp;(Use &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;his&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39; in place of&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;one&amp;#39;s&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39;)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;are preventable through vaccination&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error in the given sentence is the use of&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;are&amp;quot; after &amp;quot;Measles.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; The correct form should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;is&amp;quot; because &amp;quot;Measles&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;a singular noun.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Corrected sentence: &lt;strong&gt;Measles&lt;/strong&gt;, sometimes a highly contagious and potentially serious disease, &lt;strong&gt;is preventable through vaccination &lt;/strong&gt;and public health measures.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When&lt;strong&gt; a singular noun&lt;/strong&gt; is followed by &lt;strong&gt;additional information&lt;/strong&gt;, the &lt;strong&gt;verb&lt;/strong&gt; should &lt;strong&gt;agree with the singular noun.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Example:&lt;/em&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Incorrect: &lt;strong&gt;Traffic&lt;/strong&gt;, often a source of frustration for commuters, &lt;strong&gt;are&lt;/strong&gt; unavoidable during rush hours.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Correct: &lt;strong&gt;Traffic&lt;/strong&gt;, often a source of frustration for commuters, &lt;strong&gt;is&lt;/strong&gt; unavoidable during rush hours.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the corrected example, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;is&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is used &lt;strong&gt;to agree with the singular noun &amp;quot;Traffic&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;when additional information follows it.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Option 2&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The part of the sentence that contains a&lt;strong&gt; grammatical error &lt;/strong&gt;is:&lt;em&gt; &amp;quot;Shyam, so good with weapons, fail to find the words&amp;quot;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;error&lt;/strong&gt; here is with the &lt;strong&gt;subject-verb agreement.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The subject&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Shyam&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is singular, and so the verb should also be singular to match.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verb&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;fail&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is in the plural form, so it should be replaced with &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;fails&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; to correct the error.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the &lt;strong&gt;correct sentence &lt;/strong&gt;is: &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;Shyam, so good with weapons, fails to find the words to tell him that everything he&amp;rsquo;d done so far, all the compromises he&amp;rsquo;d made, had been for love.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;that he should to&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is grammatically incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here,&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;that he should&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;should be used instead of&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;that he should to&amp;#39;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct form is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;should work.&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;should&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is&lt;strong&gt; a modal verb,&lt;/strong&gt; which is always followed by the base form of the verb (also known as the infinitive without &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;to&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;). In this case, the correct &lt;strong&gt;base form &lt;/strong&gt;of the verb is &amp;quot;work,&amp;quot; not &amp;quot;to work.&amp;quot;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;We &lt;strong&gt;planned to take&lt;/strong&gt; a holiday.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;u&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;The teacher suggested&lt;strong&gt; &lt;u&gt;that he should&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; work harder to improve his grades.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;b&gt;Option 2)&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence is trying &lt;strong&gt;to convey that the film is renowned for being one of the most humorous films ever made.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&lt;strong&gt; correct comparative form&lt;/strong&gt; to use in this context should be the superlative form&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;funniest&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; instead of the positive form&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;funny&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;​When comparing three or more items, we use&lt;strong&gt; the superlative form.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For adjectives with one or&lt;strong&gt; two syllables, we typically add &amp;#39;-est&amp;#39; to the adjective (e.g., funny &amp;rarr; funniest).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Examples:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is &lt;strong&gt;the most &lt;/strong&gt;beautiful garden I have ever seen.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;She is&lt;strong&gt; the smartest&lt;/strong&gt; student in the class.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct statement is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;This film is a non-stop riot that many cite as one of&lt;u&gt; the funniest&lt;/u&gt; films of all time.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Other options are incorrect:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;No rectification needed&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is&lt;strong&gt; incorrect&lt;/strong&gt; because the sentence needs a superlative form.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;More funny&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is&lt;strong&gt; incorrect&lt;/strong&gt; because it is not the correct form of comparison.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Funnier&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is&lt;strong&gt; incorrect &lt;/strong&gt;because it is the comparative form and not the superlative.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
